00:04:36.430 --> 00:04:37.747
So band gap.

00:04:37.747 --> 00:04:38.955
Very, very basic description.

00:04:41.650 --> 00:04:45.740
If you've never been
exposed to band gaps before,

00:04:45.740 --> 00:04:48.090
the reason it's important
is because the band gap

00:04:48.090 --> 00:04:50.370
is going to define
what color, what

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:52.550
portion of the solar
spectrum that material

00:04:52.550 --> 00:04:55.410
absorbs light most efficiently.

00:04:55.410 --> 00:05:00.140
How a band gap forms is related
to the atomic structure.

00:05:00.140 --> 00:05:04.270
Think of bonds as essentially
why stuff is tough.

00:05:04.270 --> 00:05:06.260
If the mechanical
engineers in the room,

00:05:06.260 --> 00:05:08.750
if you remember
linear elasticity,

00:05:08.750 --> 00:05:10.360
those bonds are
what are essentially

00:05:10.360 --> 00:05:12.193
forming those springs
between the atoms that

00:05:12.193 --> 00:05:15.170
are keeping them, the
material, from flying apart.

00:05:15.170 --> 00:05:17.220
There is also a very
interesting property here,

00:05:17.220 --> 00:05:18.920
that if you have
a bound electron,

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:21.360
it's usually not moving
very far that atom.

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:24.450
It's usually in a very
localized electronic state

00:05:24.450 --> 00:05:26.120
close to that atom.

00:05:26.120 --> 00:05:30.500
So if you were to apply a
resistance meter, an Ohm meter,

00:05:30.500 --> 00:05:33.630
to your device to measure
the resistance across it,

00:05:33.630 --> 00:05:36.020
and you had just
bound electrons,

00:05:36.020 --> 00:05:38.810
you would measure a very,
very low current passing

00:05:38.810 --> 00:05:39.870
through that material.

00:05:39.870 --> 00:05:43.070
Because there would be very few
free charge carriers to move

00:05:43.070 --> 00:05:45.609
in that applied field, when
you apply the two probes

00:05:45.609 --> 00:05:47.650
and there's a little
battery in here that applies

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:49.930
a field across the
material, you wouldn't

00:05:49.930 --> 00:05:51.644
be able to measure
much current flow,

00:05:51.644 --> 00:05:54.060
because there wouldn't be too
many free electrons to carry

00:05:54.060 --> 00:05:55.380
that current.

00:05:55.380 --> 00:05:58.159
So the bound
electrons essentially

00:05:58.159 --> 00:05:59.700
enhance the strength
of the material.

00:05:59.700 --> 00:06:02.490
But it doesn't help us from a
semiconductor point of view.

00:06:02.490 --> 00:06:04.860
What we need are
excited electrons.

00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:07.260
And excited electrons are
why materials conduct.

00:06:07.260 --> 00:06:09.532
So let's imagine we have a bond.

00:06:09.532 --> 00:06:10.990
For example, in
this material right

00:06:10.990 --> 00:06:16.915
here, these gray lines
are really two electrons

00:06:16.915 --> 00:06:18.040
that are covalently bonded.

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:19.706
Essentially two
electrons-- one electron

00:06:19.706 --> 00:06:22.500
from each little black circle
representing a carbon atom.

00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:24.740
And each electron associated
with that carbon atom

00:06:24.740 --> 00:06:27.670
is shared with the other,
in a covalent bond.

00:06:27.670 --> 00:06:29.420
And for the chemists
in the room, more

00:06:29.420 --> 00:06:31.410
precisely, you have
sp3 hybridized orbitals

00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:33.330
in this diamond cubic
crystal structure.

00:06:33.330 --> 00:06:35.720
For everyone else, these
are shared electrons

00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:37.880
in a covalent bonding
configuration.

00:06:37.880 --> 00:06:39.762
Now if light comes in
with enough energy,

00:06:39.762 --> 00:06:41.970
it can excite an electron
from that covalently bonded

00:06:41.970 --> 00:06:44.710
state into an excited state,
where it can then roam freely

00:06:44.710 --> 00:06:46.147
throughout the lattice.

00:06:46.147 --> 00:06:47.980
And that's the nature
of charge excitations.

00:06:47.980 --> 00:06:49.605
So the big question
that we have to ask

00:06:49.605 --> 00:06:51.980
ourselves is, what
color of light

00:06:51.980 --> 00:06:54.480
will this material
absorb most effectively?

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:56.560
Will those electrons
in the covalent bonds

00:06:56.560 --> 00:06:58.722
absorb light and be
excited into a state

00:06:58.722 --> 00:07:00.680
where they can roam freely
around the material,

00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:03.500
and ultimately
conduct electricity?

00:07:03.500 --> 00:07:04.000
OK.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.230
So the answer to that
question is not simple.

00:07:08.230 --> 00:07:11.770
Understanding how
a band gap forms

00:07:11.770 --> 00:07:14.590
can be an entire semester
of quantum physics.

00:07:14.590 --> 00:07:18.230
But what we're going to do is
do it in a three step approach.

00:07:18.230 --> 00:07:19.990
Simple, very, very
simple explanations

00:07:19.990 --> 00:07:22.830
that hopefully
everyone will get.

00:07:22.830 --> 00:07:24.730
The next most
simple explanation,

00:07:24.730 --> 00:07:28.100
which hopefully 80% of
you will get, and then

00:07:28.100 --> 00:07:31.410
perhaps a more detailed
explanation that only a few

00:07:31.410 --> 00:07:32.540
of you will get.

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:34.560
But the idea is
to really progress

00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:38.120
in levels of explanation.

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:40.411
So let me go back one step.

00:07:40.411 --> 00:07:40.910
Yeah.

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:43.502
The band gap energy can
be most simply understood

00:07:43.502 --> 00:07:44.960
as a finite amount
of energy needed

00:07:44.960 --> 00:07:47.170
to excite a highly
localized electron

00:07:47.170 --> 00:07:49.720
into a de-localized excited
state in the semiconductor

00:07:49.720 --> 00:07:52.920
where it can move
around the crystal.

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:53.670
OK.

00:07:53.670 --> 00:07:56.620
So this is the description
of the band gap,

00:07:56.620 --> 00:07:59.100
how a band gap forms that
you'll see in many chemistry

00:07:59.100 --> 00:07:59.625
textbooks.

00:07:59.625 --> 00:08:02.000
And I like it, because it's
something that you can really

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.654
grasp and understand.

00:08:04.654 --> 00:08:06.320
We have to start with
the simple premise

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:10.330
that electrons are a type of
particle called a fermion.

00:08:10.330 --> 00:08:11.350
What is a fermion?

00:08:11.350 --> 00:08:14.240
Let's refresh our
basic physics here.

00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:16.870
What means a fermion?

00:08:16.870 --> 00:08:18.010
Spin one half.

00:08:18.010 --> 00:08:21.430
And it also means-- can two
fermions occupy the same state?

00:08:21.430 --> 00:08:22.100
No, they can't.

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:23.300
Bosons can.

00:08:23.300 --> 00:08:24.680
But fermions cannot.

00:08:24.680 --> 00:08:27.200
And so what happens when you
put two fermions together

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:28.540
in a system?

00:08:28.540 --> 00:08:32.340
And say we have
discretized quantum states.

00:08:32.340 --> 00:08:34.320
We begin filling up from
the bottom up, right?

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:35.190
Typically.

00:08:35.190 --> 00:08:37.900
So the lowest energy
states get occupied first.

00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:40.735
You have, for example, spin up,
spin down in your s orbital.

00:08:40.735 --> 00:08:43.110
And then they begin populating
the next electron orbital.

00:08:43.110 --> 00:08:46.060
Once that's filled, you go to
the next one, and the next one.

00:08:46.060 --> 00:08:48.340
So if we have one
atom in isolation,

00:08:48.340 --> 00:08:50.490
the easiest example
is that hydrogen atom,

00:08:50.490 --> 00:08:52.620
for those who took quantum
mechanics, who actually

00:08:52.620 --> 00:08:55.520
calculated the energy
of the bound electron

00:08:55.520 --> 00:08:59.410
there in the ground state of the
hydrogen atom, around 13.6 eV.

00:08:59.410 --> 00:09:03.870
So imagine now you take a
silicon atom, or carbon atom,

00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:05.930
or something else,
a little bit bigger,

00:09:05.930 --> 00:09:08.160
more electrons in its structure.

00:09:08.160 --> 00:09:11.660
So you have the core,
the 1s orbital filled.

00:09:11.660 --> 00:09:14.440
And then you start
progressing outward.

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:15.840
2s2p and so forth.

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:17.834
And so you begin
filling up the orbitals.

00:09:17.834 --> 00:09:19.000
Let's see atomic separation.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.830
So imagine that we have our
atoms infinitely separated.

00:09:21.830 --> 00:09:23.780
So we have just one
atom in the middle

00:09:23.780 --> 00:09:26.170
of an infinite lonely space.

00:09:26.170 --> 00:09:27.160
One atom.

00:09:27.160 --> 00:09:30.160
And we would have discrete
energy levels corresponding

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:33.080
to the different orbitals,
the different orbitals

00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:35.330
around the nucleus.

00:09:35.330 --> 00:09:37.190
Now imagine the atom
is no longer lonely.

00:09:37.190 --> 00:09:38.374
It now has a partner.

00:09:38.374 --> 00:09:40.790
And you bring those two atoms
closer and closer and closer

00:09:40.790 --> 00:09:41.590
together.

00:09:41.590 --> 00:09:43.870
That's this d getting
closer and closer together.

00:09:43.870 --> 00:09:44.650
What happens?

00:09:44.650 --> 00:09:46.990
Well, electrons are fermions.

00:09:46.990 --> 00:09:50.610
They don't like occupying
the same electronic state.

00:09:50.610 --> 00:09:53.236
So first, the first
shell that's going

00:09:53.236 --> 00:09:54.610
to quote, unquote
see each other,

00:09:54.610 --> 00:09:56.776
the first electron shell
that will interact is what?

00:09:56.776 --> 00:09:59.090
Is it the outermost,
or the innermost?

00:09:59.090 --> 00:09:59.650
Outermost.

00:09:59.650 --> 00:10:00.200
Right?

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:02.140
Because they're the
closest together.

00:10:02.140 --> 00:10:04.098
So you're moving the two
atoms closer together,

00:10:04.098 --> 00:10:06.890
that outermost shell will
begin to quote, unquote see

00:10:06.890 --> 00:10:08.060
the other atom.

00:10:08.060 --> 00:10:10.610
And those electrons will say,
hey, you're occupying my state.

00:10:10.610 --> 00:10:12.610
And what will happen is
they'll begin splitting,

00:10:12.610 --> 00:10:15.800
in energy level, and that's
what you see right here.

00:10:15.800 --> 00:10:18.840
What this is representing is not
just two atoms coming together,

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:21.199
but a multitude of
atoms coming together.

00:10:21.199 --> 00:10:22.990
And we have to really
imagine, for example,

00:10:22.990 --> 00:10:25.920
and in most matter, we have
something in the order of 10

00:10:25.920 --> 00:10:31.620
to the 22, 10 to the 23
atoms per cubic centimeter.

00:10:31.620 --> 00:10:34.020
So atoms per cubic centimeter.

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:36.090
Fun math, just total aside.

00:10:36.090 --> 00:10:38.990
If anybody talks about
teletransporttion,

00:10:38.990 --> 00:10:41.020
think about the number
of atoms in your body.

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:43.140
And assign an
xyz-coordinate to them,

00:10:43.140 --> 00:10:47.276
and then calculate the
amount of data in terabytes.

00:10:47.276 --> 00:10:48.900
And then calculate
our Ethernet speeds,

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:50.750
and try to figure out how
long it would take to transmit

00:10:50.750 --> 00:10:52.330
that data to the other side.

00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:53.230
Anyway.

00:10:53.230 --> 00:10:54.730
So this is to give
you an impression

00:10:54.730 --> 00:10:57.590
of the density of atoms
within the cubic centimeter.

00:10:57.590 --> 00:10:59.450
So you have a lot of
atoms coming together,

00:10:59.450 --> 00:11:02.280
even though the electron
wave function can

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:05.450
be highly localized, they still
interfere with each other.

00:11:05.450 --> 00:11:07.440
There's still enough
atoms coming together

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:08.850
that you have this interference.

00:11:08.850 --> 00:11:12.130
And it's not just two electron
states, but many of them

00:11:12.130 --> 00:11:16.290
that are splitting, that
are forming a band of states

00:11:16.290 --> 00:11:18.640
because no two electrons
can occupy the same energy

00:11:18.640 --> 00:11:20.710
level as these atoms
are coming together.

00:11:20.710 --> 00:11:23.130
Now, as they become closer
and closer and closer,

00:11:23.130 --> 00:11:25.750
it's not only that outer
shell that begins interacting.

00:11:25.750 --> 00:11:28.130
It's the next most outer shell.

00:11:28.130 --> 00:11:29.890
This one, here, that
begins interacting.

00:11:29.890 --> 00:11:33.900
And finally another
shell, and another shell.

00:11:33.900 --> 00:11:36.660
And so at some
equilibrium distance,

00:11:36.660 --> 00:11:38.330
the equilibrium
distance here defined

00:11:38.330 --> 00:11:40.810
as the attractive
potential between atoms.

00:11:40.810 --> 00:11:44.030
There's an energy gain
by forming that bond.

00:11:44.030 --> 00:11:46.530
And the repulsive
force of the nuclei,

00:11:46.530 --> 00:11:48.567
their large concentration
of positive charge

00:11:48.567 --> 00:11:50.650
in the nucleus, that if
you tried pushing them too

00:11:50.650 --> 00:11:52.990
close together, they'll repel.

00:11:52.990 --> 00:11:55.840
This balance of forces,
the attractive potential

00:11:55.840 --> 00:11:58.840
due to that bond formation, the
repulsive force to the nucleic,

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:01.220
results in an equilibrium
bond distance,

00:12:01.220 --> 00:12:03.390
d, shown here as
this dotted line.

00:12:03.390 --> 00:12:06.390
And at that equilibrium bond
distance, some of the orbitals

00:12:06.390 --> 00:12:09.050
will be forming bands and
other orbitals will still

00:12:09.050 --> 00:12:11.130
be discrete, namely
the core orbitals

00:12:11.130 --> 00:12:12.200
will still be discrete.

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:15.500
The outermost orbitals
here will be forming bands.

00:12:15.500 --> 00:12:19.770
Now an interesting thing
happens when it just so occurs,

00:12:19.770 --> 00:12:21.650
and say, for example,
in the system right

00:12:21.650 --> 00:12:23.980
here, this shell is filled.

00:12:23.980 --> 00:12:25.430
This shell is filled.

00:12:25.430 --> 00:12:28.470
This shell is completely filled.

00:12:28.470 --> 00:12:30.330
And let's imagine that
this orbital exists,

00:12:30.330 --> 00:12:32.040
but it's unpopulated.

00:12:32.040 --> 00:12:33.090
You ran out of electrons.

00:12:33.090 --> 00:12:34.930
And you started
filling in the orbitals

00:12:34.930 --> 00:12:35.900
of this atom over here.

00:12:35.900 --> 00:12:37.800
You had enough for this orbital,
that orbital, that orbital,

00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:38.850
but then you ran
out of electrons.

00:12:38.850 --> 00:12:40.140
You didn't have anything more.

00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:42.370
And this band of
states was empty.

00:12:42.370 --> 00:12:45.740
So the band of allowed
states exists up there,

00:12:45.740 --> 00:12:46.660
but it's empty.

00:12:46.660 --> 00:12:49.200
And this band right here
exists, and it's filled.

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:51.750
These core states exist,
and they're filled as well.

00:12:51.750 --> 00:12:53.930
So the action is really
happening right here.

00:12:53.930 --> 00:12:58.370
If light comes in, if
visible light comes in,

00:12:58.370 --> 00:13:01.170
it's probably going to excite an
electron from this filled band

00:13:01.170 --> 00:13:04.970
right here to somewhere in
this unoccupied band up there.

00:13:04.970 --> 00:13:08.870
And this gap, right here,
is an interesting thing.

00:13:08.870 --> 00:13:13.300
There is no stable
electron orbital.

00:13:13.300 --> 00:13:16.770
If you were somehow to take
an electron with that given

00:13:16.770 --> 00:13:19.406
energy, this energy
here, from the vacuum

00:13:19.406 --> 00:13:21.030
and stick it inside
of the system here,

00:13:21.030 --> 00:13:24.840
it would quickly decay
into a stable orbital.

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:27.480
So this is a prohibited
band of states.

00:13:27.480 --> 00:13:29.710
There is no stable
orbital for that electron

00:13:29.710 --> 00:13:31.030
to exist at that energy.

00:13:31.030 --> 00:13:34.800
And hence we call it a band gap.

00:13:34.800 --> 00:13:36.490
The reason band gaps
are interesting,

00:13:36.490 --> 00:13:38.890
is because different materials
have different, or can

00:13:38.890 --> 00:13:40.181
have different, size band gaps.

00:13:40.181 --> 00:13:42.200
Some don't have a
band gap at all.

00:13:42.200 --> 00:13:45.600
Most of those that don't
have a band gap, because you

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:49.109
have a band of states like
this one that's partially full.

00:13:49.109 --> 00:13:50.650
Let's imagine we
have three electrons

00:13:50.650 --> 00:13:51.649
in this band right here.

00:13:51.649 --> 00:13:52.650
One, two, three.

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:55.840
And then we have these other
four empty states about it.

00:13:55.840 --> 00:13:58.010
In fact, you have a
partially filled band.

00:13:58.010 --> 00:13:59.740
And let's imagine,
instead of just having

00:13:59.740 --> 00:14:02.210
seven states within that band,
we had a multitude of states

00:14:02.210 --> 00:14:03.570
within that band.

00:14:03.570 --> 00:14:04.910
Almost too many to count.

00:14:04.910 --> 00:14:08.410
And now, with even the
slightest of energy,

00:14:08.410 --> 00:14:10.950
we could excite an
electron from this state

00:14:10.950 --> 00:14:14.470
into that state
plus little delta.

00:14:14.470 --> 00:14:16.600
That would be a metal.

00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:18.830
Now if we had a
really big band gap,

00:14:18.830 --> 00:14:20.929
we wouldn't be able
to absorb much light.

00:14:20.929 --> 00:14:22.720
Because you'd need a
large amount of energy

00:14:22.720 --> 00:14:25.430
to excite across that band gap.

00:14:25.430 --> 00:14:27.600
And that would be an
example of, say, glass.

00:14:27.600 --> 00:14:28.987
Where light would come in.

00:14:28.987 --> 00:14:31.320
Most of our visible spectrum
makes it through the glass,

00:14:31.320 --> 00:14:34.500
and that's why we see
through the other side.

00:14:34.500 --> 00:14:36.750
And diamonds as well.

00:14:36.750 --> 00:14:37.420
OK.

00:14:37.420 --> 00:14:39.410
So let's review.

00:14:39.410 --> 00:14:41.980
An atom in isolation has
discrete electron energy

00:14:41.980 --> 00:14:42.510
levels.

00:14:42.510 --> 00:14:44.210
And on this diagram
right here, it's

00:14:44.210 --> 00:14:47.040
represented with this d,
the atomic separation being

00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:47.610
way out here.

00:14:47.610 --> 00:14:49.740
We have discrete energy levels.

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:52.410
And that we can remember from
our basic physics, especially

00:14:52.410 --> 00:14:54.020
the hydrogen atom.

00:14:54.020 --> 00:14:55.970
And as atoms move
closer together,

00:14:55.970 --> 00:14:58.510
as in a crystal, where you
have a regularly repeating

00:14:58.510 --> 00:15:02.010
arrangements of atoms, the
electron wave functions begin

00:15:02.010 --> 00:15:05.000
overlapping, and since
electrons are fermions,

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:09.250
meaning that the two electrons
can't occupy the same state,

00:15:09.250 --> 00:15:13.969
you have a splitting of those
energy levels forming bands.

00:15:13.969 --> 00:15:16.510
And you can see the splitting
as you move from right to left,

00:15:16.510 --> 00:15:18.860
as you move from
further to closer,

00:15:18.860 --> 00:15:20.847
on these diagrams right here.

00:15:20.847 --> 00:15:22.930
First starting with the
outermost states, the most

00:15:22.930 --> 00:15:25.550
valence of electron orbitals,
and then slowly moving

00:15:25.550 --> 00:15:27.950
into the core states as well.

00:15:27.950 --> 00:15:30.450
And the gap between
bands denoting an energy

00:15:30.450 --> 00:15:33.800
range in which no stable orbital
exists is called a band gap.

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:35.800
Sometimes you'll see it
all written as one word.

00:15:35.800 --> 00:15:39.105
Sometimes there will be a space
between the band and the gap.

00:15:39.105 --> 00:15:39.980
Any questions so far?

00:15:42.820 --> 00:15:44.930
OK.

00:15:44.930 --> 00:15:48.780
So now this explanation should
be relatively straightforward.

00:15:48.780 --> 00:15:50.780
What I want you to
log into your ram,

00:15:50.780 --> 00:15:52.375
because we're going into some
more detailed explanations,

00:15:52.375 --> 00:15:54.360
and I want to set a
marker, a flag, so we

00:15:54.360 --> 00:15:55.736
can come back here afterward.

00:15:55.736 --> 00:15:58.110
And even if you're lost with
the subsequent explanations,

00:15:58.110 --> 00:15:59.090
you still get this one.

00:15:59.090 --> 00:15:59.650
Right?

00:15:59.650 --> 00:16:01.286
So remember these three points.

00:16:01.286 --> 00:16:03.410
If you make a note of them
in your notes, and we're

00:16:03.410 --> 00:16:07.230
going to move on to a few
more explanations here.

00:16:07.230 --> 00:16:12.660
OK, so another way of looking
at this which really builds

00:16:12.660 --> 00:16:15.320
on the folks who have had a more
advanced physics backgrounds,

00:16:15.320 --> 00:16:19.400
is that the wave function
of an electron, inside

00:16:19.400 --> 00:16:22.520
of a crystal-- if
you recall the wave

00:16:22.520 --> 00:16:25.510
function of an electron in
free space, we have what

00:16:25.510 --> 00:16:27.980
is called the plane wave
equation for the electron.

00:16:27.980 --> 00:16:31.720
It's this regular repeating,
nice stable function.

00:16:31.720 --> 00:16:35.660
Now if we introduce that
electron into a crystal,

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:40.620
it's almost like an infinitely
repeating system of atoms.

00:16:40.620 --> 00:16:42.640
And so you could
envision that you

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:45.410
could describe the wave
function of that electron

00:16:45.410 --> 00:16:47.860
as a combination
of a plane wave,

00:16:47.860 --> 00:16:50.450
but perturbed by that
locally repeating potential

00:16:50.450 --> 00:16:52.450
from the atomic nuclei.

00:16:52.450 --> 00:16:54.320
And let me be more
specific about

00:16:54.320 --> 00:16:55.720
regular repeating potential.

00:16:55.720 --> 00:16:59.310
What I mean is that you have
a series of nuclei here,

00:16:59.310 --> 00:17:02.360
and if you imagine the electron
potential around these nuclei,

00:17:02.360 --> 00:17:04.530
there is a propensity
for the election

00:17:04.530 --> 00:17:07.109
to be bound by the atom.

00:17:07.109 --> 00:17:10.190
And so as it's moving along,
instead of just a free plane

00:17:10.190 --> 00:17:13.359
wave, now it's almost like
driving along a bumpy road,

00:17:13.359 --> 00:17:15.780
bump, bump, bump.

00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:18.550
And so the wave
function of the electron

00:17:18.550 --> 00:17:20.780
can be described as this
combination or product

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:23.619
of the wave function
of a plane wave,

00:17:23.619 --> 00:17:27.369
envelope function describing
the electron localization.

00:17:27.369 --> 00:17:29.670
So you have this
localized function here

00:17:29.670 --> 00:17:34.480
and the delocalized function
describing the plane wave

00:17:34.480 --> 00:17:36.930
behavior of the electron as
it moves through space inside

00:17:36.930 --> 00:17:38.350
of the crystal.

00:17:38.350 --> 00:17:42.270
Now what we have as an
easy way to describe this

00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:45.050
mathematically, is we
make an approximation.

00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:50.410
Instead of describing
this potential in detail,

00:17:50.410 --> 00:17:54.280
the easiest way to do this is
to describe this square well

00:17:54.280 --> 00:17:55.450
potential.

00:17:55.450 --> 00:17:57.659
We have a so-called
Kronig-Penney idealization

00:17:57.659 --> 00:17:59.200
of the repeating
Coulombic potential.

00:17:59.200 --> 00:18:01.050
It's easier to
solve numerically.

00:18:01.050 --> 00:18:03.250
And then essentially
what we do is

00:18:03.250 --> 00:18:07.350
we solve Schrodinger's equation
for two possible solutions.

00:18:07.350 --> 00:18:09.550
One is for the electron
wave function centered

00:18:09.550 --> 00:18:11.040
on the atoms themselves.

00:18:11.040 --> 00:18:13.320
So that would be
the bound state.

00:18:13.320 --> 00:18:17.840
And the other is we solve the
equation for electron function

00:18:17.840 --> 00:18:19.410
centered between the atoms.

00:18:19.410 --> 00:18:23.420
So essentially in the
unbound state, right here.

00:18:23.420 --> 00:18:27.032
Which do you think will have
the higher energy level?

00:18:27.032 --> 00:18:28.240
In between the states, right?

00:18:28.240 --> 00:18:31.620
Because if the electron wave
function is centered over here,

00:18:31.620 --> 00:18:34.980
it's further away from the
positive charge of the nuclei.

00:18:34.980 --> 00:18:37.290
You need more energy to
put it into that position.

00:18:37.290 --> 00:18:40.870
It's an unbound state, but it's
also at a higher excited energy

00:18:40.870 --> 00:18:41.510
level.

00:18:41.510 --> 00:18:44.000
Whereas if it's bound
around the atoms themselves,

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:47.860
you would have a
lower energy state.

00:18:47.860 --> 00:18:50.890
In this delta of energy
levels between the bound

00:18:50.890 --> 00:18:53.730
and the excited states
represents the band gap

00:18:53.730 --> 00:18:57.100
of the semiconductor in
this simple approximation

00:18:57.100 --> 00:18:58.190
right here.

00:18:58.190 --> 00:19:01.290
Now you can take that one step
further and say, well, gee,

00:19:01.290 --> 00:19:03.030
if I could solve
that in one dimension

00:19:03.030 --> 00:19:04.780
in a very simple
case, why don't I

00:19:04.780 --> 00:19:07.830
put a three dimensional
structure in place,

00:19:07.830 --> 00:19:11.729
such as a real crystal, and then
solve the Schrodinger equation?

00:19:11.729 --> 00:19:12.770
And sure you can do that.

00:19:12.770 --> 00:19:13.895
You can definitely do that.

00:19:13.895 --> 00:19:18.210
It becomes much more complicated
solution numerically,

00:19:18.210 --> 00:19:21.230
but the general principle
stays roughly the same.

00:19:21.230 --> 00:19:23.870
You can add several more
tricks, and bells, and whistles.

00:19:23.870 --> 00:19:26.906
And of course, I would
probably emphasize

00:19:26.906 --> 00:19:28.280
that the solution
could either be

00:19:28.280 --> 00:19:31.180
done numerically or you
could use the symmetry

00:19:31.180 --> 00:19:33.430
relations of the
crystal to develop

00:19:33.430 --> 00:19:37.940
a very simple expression
of the crystal,

00:19:37.940 --> 00:19:41.830
minimizing the
redundant directions

00:19:41.830 --> 00:19:43.660
inside of the crystal,
collapsing it down

00:19:43.660 --> 00:19:46.420
into the bare essential
to describe that crystal

00:19:46.420 --> 00:19:47.350
structure.

00:19:47.350 --> 00:19:53.690
And we would have some uniform
energy space that looks,

00:19:53.690 --> 00:19:56.150
for example, represented by
this yellowish surface, where

00:19:56.150 --> 00:19:58.191
you'd have an isopotential
inside of your crystal

00:19:58.191 --> 00:20:00.110
structure.

00:20:00.110 --> 00:20:03.970
So these are different ways of
looking at the band gap inside

00:20:03.970 --> 00:20:05.465
of a semiconductor crystal.

00:20:05.465 --> 00:20:07.840
If you're really interested,
and for the advance reading,

00:20:07.840 --> 00:20:09.673
I would definitely
suggest this book called,

00:20:09.673 --> 00:20:12.750
Fundamentals of Semiconductors,
by Professor Peter Yu,

00:20:12.750 --> 00:20:15.200
now retired at UC Berkeley.

00:20:15.200 --> 00:20:17.280
Very nice explanation.

00:20:17.280 --> 00:20:20.160
Uses an elegant
application of group theory

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:26.210
to derive the band structure
of a semiconductor in detail.

00:20:26.210 --> 00:20:29.523
So let's hop back to this one,
real quick-- actually, yeah?

00:20:29.523 --> 00:20:30.898
AUDIENCE: I'm just
curious if you

00:20:30.898 --> 00:20:32.906
could tell us the name
of the equation that

00:20:32.906 --> 00:20:34.670
was at the top of--

00:20:34.670 --> 00:20:37.330
PROFESSOR: Sure.

00:20:37.330 --> 00:20:37.980
Absolutely.

00:20:37.980 --> 00:20:42.503
So what we're describing here
is essentially the e to the ikx,

00:20:42.503 --> 00:20:45.440
or e to the ikr,
essentially describing

00:20:45.440 --> 00:20:46.790
that periodic potential.

00:20:46.790 --> 00:20:50.450
And then in essentially
an envelope function.

00:20:50.450 --> 00:20:52.599
So, yeah, that would
be the wave function

00:20:52.599 --> 00:20:54.890
that would be introduced into
the Schrodinger equation.

00:20:58.810 --> 00:21:00.850
So let's go back to
here really quickly,

00:21:00.850 --> 00:21:03.590
because I don't want to
get us lost in the weeds.

00:21:03.590 --> 00:21:06.930
I want us to focus on the
main concepts at hand.

00:21:06.930 --> 00:21:09.740
Let's, from an engineering
point of view--

00:21:09.740 --> 00:21:14.470
given this formation of bands
inside of real materials,

00:21:14.470 --> 00:21:17.300
since the atoms are coming
together and forming crystals,

00:21:17.300 --> 00:21:20.830
we can envision a few
different scenarios.

00:21:20.830 --> 00:21:22.520
Let's focus on the
this band here,

00:21:22.520 --> 00:21:25.200
and that band here, and the
space in between them, the band

00:21:25.200 --> 00:21:25.740
gap.

00:21:25.740 --> 00:21:27.880
And let's assume that
we have this band

00:21:27.880 --> 00:21:30.300
here either completely
filled or partially filled,

00:21:30.300 --> 00:21:32.530
and talk about what
happens in three

00:21:32.530 --> 00:21:35.170
different extreme scenarios.

00:21:35.170 --> 00:21:38.300
In one case, when we have
the band partially filled,

00:21:38.300 --> 00:21:40.850
we have what is
known as a metal.

00:21:40.850 --> 00:21:42.640
And the reason this
case is interesting

00:21:42.640 --> 00:21:45.130
is because a very
small amount of energy

00:21:45.130 --> 00:21:48.530
is all that it would take
to excite an electron

00:21:48.530 --> 00:21:50.480
and make it to move
around the crystal.

00:21:50.480 --> 00:21:52.105
As a matter of fact,
a metal has what's

00:21:52.105 --> 00:21:56.040
called electron c, that
serves to conduct electricity

00:21:56.040 --> 00:21:59.100
at room temperature and
even at very, very, very

00:21:59.100 --> 00:22:00.900
low temperatures.

00:22:00.900 --> 00:22:02.670
Semiconductor, on
the other hand.

00:22:02.670 --> 00:22:04.964
Now semiconductor has
a finite band gap,

00:22:04.964 --> 00:22:06.380
and we'll get to
this in a minute.

00:22:06.380 --> 00:22:08.296
Let's start with the
insulator, because that's

00:22:08.296 --> 00:22:10.680
a more easy to understand case.

00:22:10.680 --> 00:22:14.240
If the band gap is
very, very, very big,

00:22:14.240 --> 00:22:16.730
then a large amount
of energy is required

00:22:16.730 --> 00:22:19.780
to excite an electron
into an unbound state,

00:22:19.780 --> 00:22:21.780
so it can move freely
across the crystal.

00:22:21.780 --> 00:22:23.560
And as a result,
you're not going

00:22:23.560 --> 00:22:26.220
to have a very large population
of electrons up here.

00:22:26.220 --> 00:22:28.380
The photo excited
carrier population,

00:22:28.380 --> 00:22:32.930
meaning the population of
charge carriers, electrons,

00:22:32.930 --> 00:22:35.960
that are excited into here
from light, is very small.

00:22:35.960 --> 00:22:37.990
And the thermally excited
carrier concentration,

00:22:37.990 --> 00:22:39.490
just some background
thermal energy,

00:22:39.490 --> 00:22:42.520
kt, Boltzmann's constant
times temperature,

00:22:42.520 --> 00:22:45.450
that energy is also going to be
insufficient to drive electrons

00:22:45.450 --> 00:22:46.520
across this band gap.

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:49.370
And as a result, you will have
a very, very small population

00:22:49.370 --> 00:22:52.780
of carriers up here.

00:22:52.780 --> 00:22:55.760
And this will be an
insulator, because you

00:22:55.760 --> 00:22:59.540
will have very few charges
to transport current.

00:22:59.540 --> 00:23:02.170
If you apply a potential
across an insulator,

00:23:02.170 --> 00:23:04.380
you will not have very
much current flow.

00:23:04.380 --> 00:23:06.790
And that's the principle
of insulating materials

00:23:06.790 --> 00:23:08.260
around wires.

00:23:08.260 --> 00:23:10.020
Actually this is in
the semiconductor.

00:23:10.020 --> 00:23:11.290
This is a polymer.

00:23:11.290 --> 00:23:14.360
But if we had, for
example, glass or diamond,

00:23:14.360 --> 00:23:18.330
that would serve as a
nice insulator as well.

00:23:18.330 --> 00:23:20.960
Now a semiconductor material
is somewhere between a metal

00:23:20.960 --> 00:23:22.180
and an insulator here.

00:23:22.180 --> 00:23:24.610
And that the band
gap is now shrinking.

00:23:24.610 --> 00:23:27.280
The band gap is small enough
to interact with lights,

00:23:27.280 --> 00:23:28.211
typically.

00:23:28.211 --> 00:23:29.960
For example, this
little piece of silicon,

00:23:29.960 --> 00:23:31.900
which I'll show in
detail in a minute,

00:23:31.900 --> 00:23:33.330
towards the end of class.

00:23:33.330 --> 00:23:35.500
It doesn't look clear,
like glass does.

00:23:35.500 --> 00:23:37.310
It looks opaque.

00:23:37.310 --> 00:23:39.090
And that's because
it's absorbing photons

00:23:39.090 --> 00:23:41.220
in the visible spectrum.

00:23:41.220 --> 00:23:43.720
But it's letting some of the
infrared photons go through it.

00:23:43.720 --> 00:23:45.178
Some of the very
low energy photons

00:23:45.178 --> 00:23:47.280
can go through the material,
because those photons

00:23:47.280 --> 00:23:49.470
have insufficient energy
to excite carriers

00:23:49.470 --> 00:23:51.830
across that band gap.

00:23:51.830 --> 00:23:55.220
So we have a semiconductor
material, defined here

00:23:55.220 --> 00:23:57.130
as having a band gap.

00:23:57.130 --> 00:24:00.100
That band gap defines the
energy of the light that

00:24:00.100 --> 00:24:01.700
is most efficiently absorbed.

00:24:01.700 --> 00:24:04.814
And any photon with energy
in excess of the band gap

00:24:04.814 --> 00:24:06.605
can also be absorbed
by that semiconductor.

