00:29:30.170 --> 00:29:31.350
That was a lot of fun

00:29:31.350 --> 00:29:33.460
But now we will be
talking about life

00:29:33.460 --> 00:29:36.050
in terms of discrete
quanta of energy,

00:29:36.050 --> 00:29:37.870
because one photon
is going to be

00:29:37.870 --> 00:29:40.060
absorbed by an electron,
an excited electron,

00:29:40.060 --> 00:29:41.560
into another state.

00:29:41.560 --> 00:29:45.340
So now we think of the photon
as having a certain energy,

00:29:45.340 --> 00:29:48.140
defined by the
wavelength of light,

00:29:48.140 --> 00:29:51.900
and that energy is going to be
given to the electron, which

00:29:51.900 --> 00:29:55.254
will then be excited inside
of our semiconductor crystal.

00:29:55.254 --> 00:29:55.920
So what happens?

00:29:55.920 --> 00:29:57.316
Well we have our sun.

00:29:57.316 --> 00:29:58.940
Here we have our
semiconductor crystal.

00:29:58.940 --> 00:30:02.780
Again, I'm representing
it in terms of e versus x.

00:30:02.780 --> 00:30:05.630
I'm saying that these
states here are filled.

00:30:05.630 --> 00:30:07.970
And these states here
are mostly empty.

00:30:07.970 --> 00:30:09.200
And these are mostly filled.

00:30:09.200 --> 00:30:11.050
Mostly empty.

00:30:11.050 --> 00:30:13.230
And this is my band
gap right here.

00:30:13.230 --> 00:30:17.410
I'm plotting e in the
ordinate and x real space

00:30:17.410 --> 00:30:18.520
in the abscissa.

00:30:18.520 --> 00:30:20.589
And again, x because,
ultimately, we'll

00:30:20.589 --> 00:30:22.630
be looking at the cross
section of the solar cell

00:30:22.630 --> 00:30:25.570
in x, in describing how charge
gets extracted from the device.

00:30:25.570 --> 00:30:28.210
So that's why we're going
to be using x on this axis.

00:30:28.210 --> 00:30:30.510
Now we have sunlight here,
outside of our device.

00:30:30.510 --> 00:30:32.050
And it's going to
be shining light

00:30:32.050 --> 00:30:34.400
onto the semiconductor crystal.

00:30:34.400 --> 00:30:35.280
So what happens?

00:30:35.280 --> 00:30:36.859
Well, we know
intuitively that charge

00:30:36.859 --> 00:30:38.400
should be excited
from a bound states

00:30:38.400 --> 00:30:41.750
to an unbound state, where it
can move around the material.

00:30:41.750 --> 00:30:44.870
But not all light
serves this function.

00:30:44.870 --> 00:30:48.970
If we have a photon that has
an energy above the band gap

00:30:48.970 --> 00:30:53.110
energy, so e photon, meaning the
energy of the incident photon

00:30:53.110 --> 00:30:56.040
is greater than e gap, the
energy band gap, then we'll

00:30:56.040 --> 00:30:57.350
have an excitation of charge.

00:30:57.350 --> 00:31:00.670
We'll have an electron taken
from somewhere here, brought up

00:31:00.670 --> 00:31:03.060
to a higher excited
states, and it

00:31:03.060 --> 00:31:06.690
might come to settle down at the
bottom of that band of states

00:31:06.690 --> 00:31:07.730
that is allowed.

00:31:07.730 --> 00:31:10.510
A settling, if you will.

00:31:10.510 --> 00:31:14.270
But if our photon energy
is less than our band gap,

00:31:14.270 --> 00:31:15.730
we won't have this
process occur.

00:31:15.730 --> 00:31:19.450
Instead we'll have the light
going straight through it.

00:31:19.450 --> 00:31:21.720
And this is
brilliant, because you

00:31:21.720 --> 00:31:24.400
can begin to understand
the behavior of many solids

00:31:24.400 --> 00:31:25.370
in this way.

00:31:25.370 --> 00:31:26.811
Let's take a glass,
for instance.

00:31:26.811 --> 00:31:29.060
How many you have noticed
that you never get sunburned

00:31:29.060 --> 00:31:30.810
when the windows are up?

00:31:30.810 --> 00:31:33.990
But you get sunburned when you
forget to put the windows up,

00:31:33.990 --> 00:31:36.820
when you're driving around
and your arm's sticking out,

00:31:36.820 --> 00:31:38.850
you get that nice truckers tan.

00:31:38.850 --> 00:31:42.270
That's because the ultraviolet
photons have enough energy

00:31:42.270 --> 00:31:45.360
in glass to excite electrons
across the band gap.

00:31:45.360 --> 00:31:47.730
So the ultraviolet photons
gets absorbed by the glass,

00:31:47.730 --> 00:31:51.250
but the visible photons instead
are coming straight through,

00:31:51.250 --> 00:31:53.080
much like this.

00:31:53.080 --> 00:31:55.710
Now glass has a
very large band gap.

00:31:55.710 --> 00:31:58.610
Now silicon, much
smaller band gap.

00:31:58.610 --> 00:32:01.940
And in that case, in
the case of silicon,

00:32:01.940 --> 00:32:03.190
even the visible gets blocked.

00:32:03.190 --> 00:32:05.600
So silicon would make
a really crummy window.

00:32:05.600 --> 00:32:08.310
But it makes a really
great infrared window.

00:32:08.310 --> 00:32:10.050
So if you're detecting
infrared light,

00:32:10.050 --> 00:32:11.650
and want to block
out all the visible,

00:32:11.650 --> 00:32:15.310
you might consider sticking
up a filter made of silicon.

00:32:15.310 --> 00:32:18.064
And that's regularly
done in laboratories.

00:32:18.064 --> 00:32:19.480
So you can begin
to understand how

00:32:19.480 --> 00:32:22.350
light interacts with
matter, with solids,

00:32:22.350 --> 00:32:24.280
using this energy band diagram.

00:32:24.280 --> 00:32:27.810
And ultimately how these
optical absorption spectra

00:32:27.810 --> 00:32:29.360
come into being.

00:32:29.360 --> 00:32:31.580
So we studied these
optical absorption spectra

00:32:31.580 --> 00:32:32.330
in our last class.

00:32:32.330 --> 00:32:34.390
We just took them as a given.

00:32:34.390 --> 00:32:37.410
We didn't question
where they came from.

00:32:37.410 --> 00:32:40.890
Now we're going to be focusing
on this so-called turn

00:32:40.890 --> 00:32:43.030
on energy, or turn
on wave length.

00:32:43.030 --> 00:32:45.750
Remember wavelength and
energy are interchangeable.

00:32:45.750 --> 00:32:48.440
I've written down below here
the energy corresponding

00:32:48.440 --> 00:32:50.770
to a given wavelength,
around 2000 nanometers.

00:32:50.770 --> 00:32:53.160
We have an energy
of around 0.62 eV.

00:32:53.160 --> 00:32:58.480
At around 200 nanometers,
we have an energy of 6.2 eV.

00:32:58.480 --> 00:33:02.540
Since one is the reciprocal
of the other, related by hc,

00:33:02.540 --> 00:33:04.200
it's only natural
that if we change one

00:33:04.200 --> 00:33:05.750
by an order of magnitude,
we're changing the other

00:33:05.750 --> 00:33:07.874
by an order of magnitude
in the opposite direction.

00:33:07.874 --> 00:33:10.520
So we're wrapping our minds
around this interchangeability

00:33:10.520 --> 00:33:11.884
of wavelength and energy.

00:33:11.884 --> 00:33:13.300
That's important,
because we'll be

00:33:13.300 --> 00:33:17.440
referring to them very
naturally as a photon

00:33:17.440 --> 00:33:20.030
either having a certain
wavelength or a certain energy.

00:33:20.030 --> 00:33:22.550
You notice that there are
certain turn on energies.

00:33:22.550 --> 00:33:24.610
So energy is increasing
in that direction there.

00:33:24.610 --> 00:33:28.040
So as we go from
infrared to ultraviolet,

00:33:28.040 --> 00:33:30.800
the energy of the incoming
light is increasing.

00:33:30.800 --> 00:33:33.390
And if the energy is too low,
the semiconductor crystal

00:33:33.390 --> 00:33:34.360
just won't absorb.

00:33:34.360 --> 00:33:36.570
The absorptance is 0,
or very, very small.

00:33:36.570 --> 00:33:39.500
It doesn't even appear
on the log plot here.

00:33:39.500 --> 00:33:41.270
And as we begin
increasing the energy,

00:33:41.270 --> 00:33:42.770
suddenly there's like a turn on.

00:33:42.770 --> 00:33:45.500
The semiconductor begins
to absorb that light,

00:33:45.500 --> 00:33:49.450
and you begin to have this
process occur right here.

00:33:49.450 --> 00:33:52.662
You begin to go from
that red light that

00:33:52.662 --> 00:33:54.120
went straight
through the material,

00:33:54.120 --> 00:33:58.742
to this blue light example here
where we have absorption event.

