Not really at the valence band
maximum or the maximum energy

00:39:28.500 --> 00:39:32.150
level within the valence band,
these being the filled states.

00:39:32.150 --> 00:39:34.850
So this is a more
realistic representation

00:39:34.850 --> 00:39:35.910
of charge excitation.

00:39:35.910 --> 00:39:38.680
We have an electron
being excited up.

00:39:38.680 --> 00:39:41.400
And this little h plus that's
right here, who did the reading

00:39:41.400 --> 00:39:43.840
and know what that
h plus represents?

00:39:43.840 --> 00:39:44.900
A hole.

00:39:44.900 --> 00:39:46.520
So what is a hole?

00:39:46.520 --> 00:39:47.990
It's just what it sounds like.

00:39:47.990 --> 00:39:49.879
It's the absence of an electron.

00:39:49.879 --> 00:39:51.170
There used to be electron here.

00:39:51.170 --> 00:39:51.940
Now it's up there.

00:39:51.940 --> 00:39:53.640
It left behind a hole.

00:39:53.640 --> 00:39:55.210
An easy way to
think about a hole

00:39:55.210 --> 00:39:59.970
is if you're in a big traffic
jam, bumper to bumper,

00:39:59.970 --> 00:40:04.510
something bad happened up ahead,
and backed up the traffic.

00:40:04.510 --> 00:40:08.520
Now imagine just removing
one car from that highway.

00:40:08.520 --> 00:40:10.100
You've created a hole.

00:40:10.100 --> 00:40:15.574
So the car that used to be
behind that hole moves forward.

00:40:15.574 --> 00:40:17.990
And the car that used to be
behind that one moves forward.

00:40:17.990 --> 00:40:20.406
And the car that used to be
behind that one moves forward.

00:40:20.406 --> 00:40:21.680
So three cars moved forward.

00:40:21.680 --> 00:40:25.420
And the hole moved
backward three places.

00:40:25.420 --> 00:40:25.920
Right.

00:40:25.920 --> 00:40:28.610
So you can either describe
the dynamics of the system

00:40:28.610 --> 00:40:30.870
as n number of
cars moving forward

00:40:30.870 --> 00:40:34.780
or one hole moving
backwards n places.

00:40:34.780 --> 00:40:38.130
It's much simpler from an
accountability point of view

00:40:38.130 --> 00:40:41.070
to be talking about one
quasi particle, a hole,

00:40:41.070 --> 00:40:43.070
rather than talking about
n cars moving forward,

00:40:43.070 --> 00:40:44.260
n electrons moving.

00:40:44.260 --> 00:40:46.760
So when we talk about
this hole right here,

00:40:46.760 --> 00:40:50.790
thermalization is going
to drive this electron

00:40:50.790 --> 00:40:54.210
to the lowest energy level
within the conduction band.

00:40:54.210 --> 00:40:56.690
And it's also going to drive
the electrons above the hole,

00:40:56.690 --> 00:40:58.387
essentially to fall
down into the hole.

00:40:58.387 --> 00:41:00.220
In other words, the
hole is going to move up

00:41:00.220 --> 00:41:02.080
to the top of the valence band.

00:41:02.080 --> 00:41:02.580
Yes.

00:41:02.580 --> 00:41:03.520
Question.

00:41:03.520 --> 00:41:05.478
AUDIENCE: Why isn't the
hole originally created

00:41:05.478 --> 00:41:07.120
at the top of the band?

00:41:07.120 --> 00:41:10.912
PROFESSOR: Well,
it really depends

00:41:10.912 --> 00:41:13.120
on what's called the matrix
element of the absorption

00:41:13.120 --> 00:41:13.659
process.

00:41:13.659 --> 00:41:15.950
In other words, what electrons
have the largest capture

00:41:15.950 --> 00:41:18.104
cross section for
that incident photon.

00:41:18.104 --> 00:41:20.020
And it is a probability
distribution function.

00:41:20.020 --> 00:41:23.980
So you will get some
electrons further down

00:41:23.980 --> 00:41:27.281
from the top of the valence
band absorbing light, as well

00:41:27.281 --> 00:41:28.780
as some of the
electrons right there

00:41:28.780 --> 00:41:31.570
at the tippy top of the
valence band absorbing light.

00:41:31.570 --> 00:41:34.440
So I'm representing, say
for example, a typical case,

00:41:34.440 --> 00:41:36.500
where you have an
electron that's

00:41:36.500 --> 00:41:39.880
not right at the top of the
valence band, and certainly not

00:41:39.880 --> 00:41:42.410
deep in the core level,
but nearish enough

00:41:42.410 --> 00:41:45.830
to the top of the valence band
absorbing that light being

00:41:45.830 --> 00:41:47.380
excited across.

00:41:47.380 --> 00:41:49.930
So in reality,
this is meant to be

00:41:49.930 --> 00:41:52.320
an arbitrary scale here,
but more representative

00:41:52.320 --> 00:41:54.110
of a whole process.

00:41:54.110 --> 00:41:56.970
And to think about this in
a more realistic sense, what

00:41:56.970 --> 00:42:01.514
you would do is you think,
OK, I've this incoming photon,

00:42:01.514 --> 00:42:03.430
and there's a certain
probability distribution

00:42:03.430 --> 00:42:06.710
function that represents the
probability of absorptance

00:42:06.710 --> 00:42:08.650
by different electrons
in my system.

00:42:08.650 --> 00:42:11.380
Which one is going to absorb
the light, let's roll the dice.

00:42:11.380 --> 00:42:12.089
Do a Monte Carlo.

00:42:12.089 --> 00:42:12.588
OK.

00:42:12.588 --> 00:42:13.990
That one absorbed it this time.

00:42:13.990 --> 00:42:15.270
That one got excited up.

00:42:15.270 --> 00:42:15.460
OK.

00:42:15.460 --> 00:42:17.418
Another photon with
identical energy coming in.

00:42:17.418 --> 00:42:18.580
Which electron absorbs it?

00:42:18.580 --> 00:42:20.060
That one.

00:42:20.060 --> 00:42:22.730
So that's the way I would
say it really works.

00:42:22.730 --> 00:42:27.590
This is a simple representation
on the lecture slide.

00:42:27.590 --> 00:42:31.590
So we have the hole going up,
and the electron going down.

00:42:31.590 --> 00:42:34.060
Both particles are relaxing.

00:42:34.060 --> 00:42:34.560
Right.

00:42:34.560 --> 00:42:37.010
So the electron is moving
to its lowest energy state

00:42:37.010 --> 00:42:40.930
and the hole is also moving
to its lowest energy state.

00:42:40.930 --> 00:42:44.160
So if you want to think about
the electron as a bowling ball,

00:42:44.160 --> 00:42:47.140
and the hole as a balloon,
you're welcome to.

00:42:47.140 --> 00:42:51.380
Whatever mechanism helps you
think through this process,

00:42:51.380 --> 00:42:54.520
use that as a crutch right
now as we move forward.

00:42:54.520 --> 00:42:56.080
Always remember
that in the system,

00:42:56.080 --> 00:42:58.120
these are electrons essentially
moving down, and filling up

00:42:58.120 --> 00:42:59.495
that hole, and
the hole is moving

00:42:59.495 --> 00:43:03.040
in the opposite direction, much
like the vacancy in a traffic

00:43:03.040 --> 00:43:05.230
jam.

00:43:05.230 --> 00:43:07.890
So again, thermalization
losses can

00:43:07.890 --> 00:43:10.700
be described by both electrons
and holes in our system,

00:43:10.700 --> 00:43:17.040
by both the rattling around of
an electron in the conduction

00:43:17.040 --> 00:43:19.370
band and the
settling of electrons

00:43:19.370 --> 00:43:20.790
here in the valence
band as well,

00:43:20.790 --> 00:43:23.840
or the rising of that hole
toward the valence band

00:43:23.840 --> 00:43:26.500
maximum and the settling of that
electron toward the conduction

00:43:26.500 --> 00:43:27.940
band minimum.

00:43:27.940 --> 00:43:31.400
So a natural question is,
how fast is this process?

00:43:31.400 --> 00:43:32.260
Can it be reversed?

00:43:32.260 --> 00:43:34.510
If we're losing all this
energy due to thermalization,

00:43:34.510 --> 00:43:38.790
can somehow we halt it and
stop it from happening?

00:43:38.790 --> 00:43:40.820
There are people trying.

00:43:40.820 --> 00:43:42.880
It is a valiant fight.

00:43:42.880 --> 00:43:46.550
This plot right here
represents what's

00:43:46.550 --> 00:43:49.665
called the density of states.

00:43:49.665 --> 00:43:51.790
We're going to get to that
in another lecture here,

00:43:51.790 --> 00:43:56.000
but I'm going to expose you
to the rough concept here.

00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:57.310
Y-axis is energy.

00:43:57.310 --> 00:43:59.820
So again, we have our
valence band maximum

00:43:59.820 --> 00:44:02.050
and our conduction
band minimum up there.

00:44:02.050 --> 00:44:04.600
X-axis here is
representing time.

00:44:04.600 --> 00:44:07.420
So we're going from the
excitation event, which

00:44:07.420 --> 00:44:09.720
