00:44:09.720 --> 00:44:13.230
Zero plus represents what this
is on the positive side, moving

00:44:13.230 --> 00:44:15.230
time forward from
the excitation event,

00:44:15.230 --> 00:44:18.090
so instantaneously after
the execution event.

00:44:18.090 --> 00:44:22.350
We had to the equilibrium
population of holes

00:44:22.350 --> 00:44:25.220
and of electrons inside of
our semiconductor system.

00:44:25.220 --> 00:44:27.660
There weren't absolutely
zero electrons

00:44:27.660 --> 00:44:29.366
in the conduction
band, because of heat.

00:44:29.366 --> 00:44:31.240
There was enough thermal
energy in our system

00:44:31.240 --> 00:44:33.210
to excite some of
those electrons across.

00:44:33.210 --> 00:44:36.210
And that's why we had that small
population of electrons there

00:44:36.210 --> 00:44:38.920
and holes down here, the
holes they left behind.

00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:41.700
Now we had a photon coming
in, high energy photon,

00:44:41.700 --> 00:44:45.190
that excited these
electrons down here up there

00:44:45.190 --> 00:44:46.160
into the valence band.

00:44:48.800 --> 00:44:51.770
Up into here, in
the valence band.

00:44:51.770 --> 00:44:55.440
And over time, this
excited population

00:44:55.440 --> 00:44:59.542
will decay down to the
conduction band minimum

00:44:59.542 --> 00:45:01.750
and valence band maximum,
the electrons and the holes

00:45:01.750 --> 00:45:02.880
respectively.

00:45:02.880 --> 00:45:05.540
And over time, when
I say over time,

00:45:05.540 --> 00:45:09.060
I'm referring to something in
the range of one picosecond, 10

00:45:09.060 --> 00:45:11.090
to the minus 12 seconds.

00:45:11.090 --> 00:45:13.540
That's like that, but faster.

00:45:13.540 --> 00:45:16.605
So we have a quick decay of
these photoexcited carriers,

00:45:16.605 --> 00:45:18.250
and so extraction
of that energy is

00:45:18.250 --> 00:45:20.750
going to be nearly impossible,
unless we do something

00:45:20.750 --> 00:45:22.737
very clever with our
crystal to prevent

00:45:22.737 --> 00:45:23.820
that decay from happening.

00:45:23.820 --> 00:45:26.230
Somehow we suppress
the phonons from being

00:45:26.230 --> 00:45:30.070
emitted at that frequency,
at least, or at that energy.

00:45:30.070 --> 00:45:32.260
So there are a lot of
people, clever people,

00:45:32.260 --> 00:45:35.526
working on this problem and
trying to prevent the decay.

00:45:35.526 --> 00:45:36.900
The next challenge,
of course, is

00:45:36.900 --> 00:45:40.570
extracting those so-called hot
carriers, the excited carriers,

00:45:40.570 --> 00:45:42.502
from your device and
keeping that energy when

00:45:42.502 --> 00:45:43.710
they're going into the metal.

00:45:43.710 --> 00:45:45.210
That's a whole
another can of worms.

00:45:45.210 --> 00:45:49.200
So we have the time
scales of thermalization,

00:45:49.200 --> 00:45:52.040
and this is why, at least
from the perspective

00:45:52.040 --> 00:45:54.840
of your homework, we're going to
treat thermalization losses as

00:45:54.840 --> 00:45:55.800
inevitable.

00:45:55.800 --> 00:45:57.740
As Harvard and MIT
students, I would

00:45:57.740 --> 00:46:00.750
urge you to never consider
anything is inevitable.

00:46:00.750 --> 00:46:02.510
If we understand the
physics well enough,

00:46:02.510 --> 00:46:04.550
we can probably
engineer a solution.

00:46:04.550 --> 00:46:09.140
But for now, let's consider this
a reality, a loss mechanism.

00:46:09.140 --> 00:46:11.530
So if we start putting
things together,

00:46:11.530 --> 00:46:15.374
if we put non absorption, which
we talked about last lecture,

00:46:15.374 --> 00:46:16.790
we actually ran
some calculations,

00:46:16.790 --> 00:46:19.110
back of the envelope, and
we calculated the thickness

00:46:19.110 --> 00:46:23.430
necessary to absorb 90% of the
photons at a given wavelength.

00:46:23.430 --> 00:46:25.390
We also know how to
calculate reflectance off

00:46:25.390 --> 00:46:27.470
of a front surface.

00:46:27.470 --> 00:46:29.890
And so we get this
third point right here.

00:46:29.890 --> 00:46:32.050
We actually got it last class.

00:46:32.050 --> 00:46:35.740
And the fourth point right here,
we intuitively understand now

00:46:35.740 --> 00:46:38.680
that if the photon comes in with
more energy than the band gap,

00:46:38.680 --> 00:46:41.950
that excess energy is going to
be lost due to thermalization.

00:46:41.950 --> 00:46:44.000
So now if we have
the solar spectrum,

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:46.130
and we know the band
gap of a semiconductor,

00:46:46.130 --> 00:46:49.830
we should be able to do a very
cursory plot of the efficiency

00:46:49.830 --> 00:46:54.550
versus band gap, versus energy.

00:46:54.550 --> 00:46:56.580
So again, we have
thermalization losses.

00:46:56.580 --> 00:46:58.150
The band gap is too small.

00:46:58.150 --> 00:47:00.980
And non absorption losses,
if the band gap is too large.

00:47:00.980 --> 00:47:04.640
And let's just do an
absurd thought experiment.

00:47:04.640 --> 00:47:06.460
If we say, OK,
I'm really, really

00:47:06.460 --> 00:47:08.220
scared of thermalization
losses, so I'm

00:47:08.220 --> 00:47:10.679
going to make the biggest band
gap material I possibly can,

00:47:10.679 --> 00:47:12.803
I'm going to have a very
low efficiency in my cell,

00:47:12.803 --> 00:47:14.420
because I'm not
absorbing any light.

00:47:14.420 --> 00:47:17.200
The solar cell will
be transparent.

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:19.920
If I'm scared of
non-absorption losses,

00:47:19.920 --> 00:47:21.920
I say, OK, I'm going to
make my band gap really,

00:47:21.920 --> 00:47:22.950
really, really tiny.

00:47:22.950 --> 00:47:25.480
I'm going to be losing a
heck of a lot of energy

00:47:25.480 --> 00:47:27.920
due to thermalization,
due to this loss mechanism

00:47:27.920 --> 00:47:28.790
right up here.

00:47:28.790 --> 00:47:30.750
And so there has to
be some happy optimum,

00:47:30.750 --> 00:47:32.360
somewhere between
the two, where we

00:47:32.360 --> 00:47:35.560
have the maximum potential
efficiency of a solar cell

00:47:35.560 --> 00:47:38.680
device, given our
solar spectrum.

00:47:38.680 --> 00:47:41.000
We're going to walk
through that right now.

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:45.480
So approximating non-absorption
losses, very first step.

00:47:45.480 --> 00:47:49.070
What we're going to do, for
our non-absorption losses,

00:47:49.070 --> 00:47:51.220
is run a very
quick approximation

00:47:51.220 --> 00:47:56.550
that any photon
with photon energy

00:47:56.550 --> 00:48:00.340
corresponding to the band gap
energy is going to be absorbed.

00:48:00.340 --> 00:48:05.396
So if our photon has a larger
energy than the band bap,

00:48:05.396 --> 00:48:06.480
it will be absorbed.

00:48:06.480 --> 00:48:08.380
If it has an energy
less than the band gap,

00:48:08.380 --> 00:48:09.670
it will not be absorbed.

00:48:09.670 --> 00:48:11.878
And that's what this plot
right here is representing.

00:48:11.878 --> 00:48:14.620
We have wavelength right
here, longer wavelength,

00:48:14.620 --> 00:48:15.920
lower energy.

00:48:15.920 --> 00:48:17.750
Smaller wavelength,
larger energy.

00:48:17.750 --> 00:48:19.600
And at some point,
we have the turn

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:22.720
on of absorption of
our device, because we

00:48:22.720 --> 00:48:26.710
have band gap at that energy.

00:48:26.710 --> 00:48:30.720
And the y-axis here,
I've plotted EQE, which

00:48:30.720 --> 00:48:32.902
is External Quantum Efficiency.

00:48:32.902 --> 00:48:35.110
I've coined the term over
here on the left-hand side.

00:48:35.110 --> 00:48:36.980
It's the efficiency
at which free charge

00:48:36.980 --> 00:48:40.690
carriers are generated by an
incident photon on the device.

00:48:40.690 --> 00:48:42.780
So one way to think
about it is if I

00:48:42.780 --> 00:48:46.140
have a EQE of 100%, that means
that for each photon that I

00:48:46.140 --> 00:48:50.040
throw at my solar cell device,
I'm generating and collecting

00:48:50.040 --> 00:48:52.160
one free carrier
from that device.

00:48:52.160 --> 00:48:56.050
One electron hole pair, if
you will, from that device.

00:48:56.050 --> 00:48:58.160
So that's plotted right here.

00:48:58.160 --> 00:48:59.800
That makes intuitive sense.

00:48:59.800 --> 00:49:01.261
This is an approximation though.

00:49:01.261 --> 00:49:03.260
And I wanted to take it
one step further, again,

00:49:03.260 --> 00:49:04.390
planting the flag right here.

00:49:04.390 --> 00:49:05.230
Because we're going
to come back to this,

00:49:05.230 --> 00:49:06.235
we're going to use this.

00:49:06.235 --> 00:49:08.360
But I wanted to go one
level deeper into the trees,

00:49:08.360 --> 00:49:10.900
for everyone else who wants
some more advanced concepts.

00:49:10.900 --> 00:49:14.260
This is the reality of how
quantum efficiency looks.

00:49:14.260 --> 00:49:17.914
Yes, we have a turn on,
depending on the material

00:49:17.914 --> 00:49:18.580
that's involved.

00:49:18.580 --> 00:49:20.970
We have silicon, gallium
arsenide, copper indium gallium

00:49:20.970 --> 00:49:25.362
diselenide, amorphous silicon,
dye sensitized solar cells,

00:49:25.362 --> 00:49:27.820
organic solar cells, a variety
of different materials right

00:49:27.820 --> 00:49:28.540
here.

00:49:28.540 --> 00:49:31.670
And their different turn
on wavelengths right here.

00:49:31.670 --> 00:49:33.630
So we have wavelengths,
different energies.

00:49:33.630 --> 00:49:36.330
Some turn on at lower energies,
others at higher energies.

00:49:36.330 --> 00:49:39.080
So this represents, more
or less, the band gap

00:49:39.080 --> 00:49:40.790
turn on energy, more or less.

00:49:40.790 --> 00:49:42.498
It also has to do with
the thickness, how

00:49:42.498 --> 00:49:43.700
it absorbs light.

00:49:43.700 --> 00:49:46.050
At the shorter
wavelengths though,

00:49:46.050 --> 00:49:48.050
instead of just
having a QE of one,

00:49:48.050 --> 00:49:50.930
going all the way out
to x-ray territory,

00:49:50.930 --> 00:49:54.070
we have a turn
off at some point.

00:49:54.070 --> 00:49:54.780
Why is that?

00:49:58.330 --> 00:50:02.320
Why in a real device
would we-- Yeah.

00:50:02.320 --> 00:50:04.260
We have glass absorbing,
on the front side,

00:50:04.260 --> 00:50:06.130
that's one real big reason.

00:50:06.130 --> 00:50:07.730
Do we have another idea?

00:50:11.710 --> 00:50:12.210
Yep.

00:50:12.210 --> 00:50:15.230
Glass absorption is
one real big one.

00:50:15.230 --> 00:50:17.650
There are other dead layers
inside of a solar cell device

00:50:17.650 --> 00:50:19.560
in the near surface
region that also absorb

00:50:19.560 --> 00:50:22.370
the light in some architecture.

00:50:22.370 --> 00:50:26.990
So it's not a perfect QE
spectrum that looks like that.

00:50:26.990 --> 00:50:29.080
But why don't we care?

00:50:29.080 --> 00:50:31.930
For the purposes of just
engineering approximation,

00:50:31.930 --> 00:50:34.470
why aren't we bothered
by these photons

00:50:34.470 --> 00:50:35.679
that we're losing down there?

00:50:35.679 --> 00:50:38.136
AUDIENCE: Because the percentage
of the solar spectrum that

00:50:38.136 --> 00:50:39.524
falls in that region is small.

00:50:39.524 --> 00:50:40.440
PROFESSOR: Absolutely.

00:50:40.440 --> 00:50:42.720
So what we're doing is an
engineering approximation

00:50:42.720 --> 00:50:46.870
right here to get to a very
first cursory efficiency

00:50:46.870 --> 00:50:50.630
calculation, neglecting
things at the extremes.

00:50:50.630 --> 00:50:53.040
Two short wavelengths,
because there's just not

00:50:53.040 --> 00:50:54.920
a whole lot of solar
flux down there.

00:50:54.920 --> 00:50:56.880
And too long wavelengths,
because again,

00:50:56.880 --> 00:50:58.880
not a whole lot of
solar flux right there.

00:50:58.880 --> 00:51:06.010
So we're going to be using this
approximation in our homeworks

00:51:06.010 --> 00:51:09.660
and that will get
us somewhat close.

00:51:09.660 --> 00:51:14.210
If we really want it to be
true, instead of using a box

00:51:14.210 --> 00:51:16.720
function like this, an
absorption box function,

00:51:16.720 --> 00:51:19.200
we would use an
absorption spectrum that

00:51:19.200 --> 00:51:24.000
looks something more like that.

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:27.180
We've used a two
absorption spectrum.

00:51:27.180 --> 00:51:29.650
And then convolute that with
the thickness of the device

00:51:29.650 --> 00:51:34.200
to calculate what fraction
of photons at each energy

00:51:34.200 --> 00:51:36.430
is absorbed inside of my device.

00:51:36.430 --> 00:51:38.629
And that would give
you a plot that

00:51:38.629 --> 00:51:39.920
looks something more like this.

00:51:39.920 --> 00:51:42.350
Instead of this
box plot up here,

00:51:42.350 --> 00:51:45.550
it might give you plot that
looks something more like this.

00:51:45.550 --> 00:51:48.790
So you'd have instead
of just a sharp turn on,

00:51:48.790 --> 00:51:50.960
if you had a one micron
thick silicon wafer,

00:51:50.960 --> 00:51:52.460
and we calculated
last class that we

00:51:52.460 --> 00:51:54.418
need somewhere around 10
microns or 100 microns

00:51:54.418 --> 00:51:56.170
to absorb light
well, if we reduce

00:51:56.170 --> 00:51:58.140
the thickness of the
wafer to 1/10 or 1/100

00:51:58.140 --> 00:51:59.910
of what's necessary
to absorb light well,

00:51:59.910 --> 00:52:02.580
we don't see that sharp
turn on at the band gap.

00:52:02.580 --> 00:52:05.067
We see rather a gradual
turn on of our silicon

00:52:05.067 --> 00:52:07.150
as we move to shorter and
shorter wavelengths that

00:52:07.150 --> 00:52:11.240
are absorbed more and more
efficiently by the device.

00:52:11.240 --> 00:52:13.870
So again, just wrapping our
head around the basic concept

00:52:13.870 --> 00:52:16.520
that we're going to use for the
purposes of our calculation,

00:52:16.520 --> 00:52:18.980
but, again, some of the
more fine structure,

00:52:18.980 --> 00:52:21.290
some of the more advanced
concepts that come into

00:52:21.290 --> 00:52:24.790
play when we're doing more
detailed calculations.

00:52:24.790 --> 00:52:27.370
Approximating
thermalization losses now.

00:52:27.370 --> 00:52:29.480
We want to calculate
the amount of energy

00:52:29.480 --> 00:52:32.650
lost of incident sunlight
lost due to thermalization,

00:52:32.650 --> 00:52:33.624
due to heat.

00:52:33.624 --> 00:52:36.290
And we're going to say here that
if the photon energy is greater

00:52:36.290 --> 00:52:37.970
than the band gap,
than the photon

00:52:37.970 --> 00:52:41.239
energy is approximately the
band gap plus thermalization.

00:52:41.239 --> 00:52:43.280
Another way to put it
would be the thermalization

00:52:43.280 --> 00:52:44.696
is approximately
the photon energy

00:52:44.696 --> 00:52:47.357
minus the band gap energy.

00:52:47.357 --> 00:52:49.190
I kind of wanted to
hide all this down here.

00:52:49.190 --> 00:52:50.472
Forget this exists right now.

00:52:50.472 --> 00:52:51.680
Let's focus on that top part.

00:52:51.680 --> 00:52:54.184
So that's the easy way
of thinking about it.

00:52:54.184 --> 00:52:55.725
We're going to be
thinking about this

00:52:55.725 --> 00:52:58.360
in terms of just
any photon coming

00:52:58.360 --> 00:52:59.950
into our device
with a larger energy

00:52:59.950 --> 00:53:02.800
than the band gap is going to
generate one electron hole pair

00:53:02.800 --> 00:53:06.850
and lose some energy
due to thermalization.

00:53:06.850 --> 00:53:10.371
The reality is that for
very high energy photons,

00:53:10.371 --> 00:53:12.870
say for example photons with
three times the band gap energy

00:53:12.870 --> 00:53:16.180
or more, you could have
electron-electron interactions.

00:53:16.180 --> 00:53:19.074
So if you excite one electron
to very highly excited state,

00:53:19.074 --> 00:53:20.990
it can bounce around and
in the process excite

00:53:20.990 --> 00:53:23.500
another electron
across the band gap.

00:53:23.500 --> 00:53:26.900
That's the case when x-rays are
incident on a piece of silicon.

00:53:26.900 --> 00:53:30.300
For instance, if you have
a 10 kilo-electron volt,

00:53:30.300 --> 00:53:34.020
so a 10,000 eV x-ray incident
on a piece of silicon,

00:53:34.020 --> 00:53:36.880
you will generate approximately
3,000 electron hole pairs

00:53:36.880 --> 00:53:38.196
with that one x-ray.

00:53:38.196 --> 00:53:40.320
Because that one x-ray is
going to take an electron

00:53:40.320 --> 00:53:42.400
and excite it to very
highly excited state,

00:53:42.400 --> 00:53:45.130
and that's going to
excite further electrons

00:53:45.130 --> 00:53:49.300
across the band gap as that
excited carrier decays,

00:53:49.300 --> 00:53:53.370
as it loses it's energy and
settles at the conduction band

00:53:53.370 --> 00:53:54.580
minimum.

00:53:54.580 --> 00:53:59.499
So we have what's called
multiple exciton generation.

00:53:59.499 --> 00:54:01.540
Sometimes we've heard it
as multiple free carrier

00:54:01.540 --> 00:54:02.450
generation.

00:54:02.450 --> 00:54:04.260
In semiconductors,
it's a hot topic,

00:54:04.260 --> 00:54:06.600
because folks would like to
take the ultraviolet portion

00:54:06.600 --> 00:54:09.650
of the spectrum, the high
energy, short wavelength,

00:54:09.650 --> 00:54:11.760
portion of the solar
spectrum, and use

00:54:11.760 --> 00:54:13.580
it to excite multiple carriers.

00:54:13.580 --> 00:54:16.940
One photon exciting multiple
carriers across the band gap.

00:54:16.940 --> 00:54:19.099
And so there's some
work, or was some work,

00:54:19.099 --> 00:54:20.390
it was a hot topic for a while.

00:54:20.390 --> 00:54:21.515
It's kind of decayed a bit.

00:54:21.515 --> 00:54:22.450
It comes in waves.

00:54:22.450 --> 00:54:24.690
It cycles, kind of
like a plane wave.

00:54:24.690 --> 00:54:27.730
There is an interest, a
general interest in the field,

00:54:27.730 --> 00:54:29.890
of how do you capture
these higher energy photons

00:54:29.890 --> 00:54:31.429
and convert them
in some usable way,

00:54:31.429 --> 00:54:33.220
instead of just having
thermalization loss,

00:54:33.220 --> 00:54:35.360
instead of just having heat.

00:54:35.360 --> 00:54:37.030
And then for really
high energy photons,

00:54:37.030 --> 00:54:39.530
gosh, you can really get
into some neat physics.

00:54:39.530 --> 00:54:42.730
I've given you a link
and cross section here.

00:54:42.730 --> 00:54:46.510
This is the electron
cross section, or actually

00:54:46.510 --> 00:54:50.280
really what it is is an
anatomic cross section,

00:54:50.280 --> 00:54:53.020
because of the electrons in
the material versus photon

00:54:53.020 --> 00:54:57.140
energy going through 10
eV out to 10 to eV 11.

00:54:57.140 --> 00:54:59.080
A very high photon energy.

00:54:59.080 --> 00:55:05.520
We're transiting from the
visible spectrum over here

00:55:05.520 --> 00:55:07.890
deep into the infrared, and
then going into the x-ray,

00:55:07.890 --> 00:55:09.390
and finally to the
gamma ray regime.

00:55:09.390 --> 00:55:11.598
There you can have a number
of interesting phenomena.

00:55:11.598 --> 00:55:14.370
You can even have an electron
hole, or electron-positron pair

00:55:14.370 --> 00:55:18.180
generation with
gigaelectron-volt incident

00:55:18.180 --> 00:55:18.977
radiation or above.

00:55:18.977 --> 00:55:20.810
We're not gonna even
talk about this regime,

00:55:20.810 --> 00:55:25.060
because the total amount of
solar flux in that regime

00:55:25.060 --> 00:55:27.285
is really tiny
compared to visible.

00:55:27.285 --> 00:55:29.410
But it's a lot of interesting,
fascinating physics.

00:55:29.410 --> 00:55:32.890
So I put it on here anyway
just to keep our approximation

00:55:32.890 --> 00:55:34.410
in focus.

00:55:34.410 --> 00:55:38.120
So again, I'm kind of mixing
the forest in the trees

00:55:38.120 --> 00:55:40.320
here to give you a
sense of the complexity.

00:55:40.320 --> 00:55:42.860
But also to give you the
tools necessary to do

00:55:42.860 --> 00:55:44.240
simple calculations.

00:55:44.240 --> 00:55:48.250
We're going to combine this
simple approximation right here

00:55:48.250 --> 00:55:50.010
of the non-absorption losses.

00:55:50.010 --> 00:55:52.992
We're going to say that
any photon with energy

00:55:52.992 --> 00:55:55.450
less than the band gap doesn't
get absorbed by our crystal.

00:55:55.450 --> 00:55:57.552
It's gone to us.

00:55:57.552 --> 00:55:59.260
And we're going to
make the approximation

00:55:59.260 --> 00:56:01.770
that any photon with
energy above the band gap

00:56:01.770 --> 00:56:05.510
will have that excess energy
loss due to thermalization.

00:56:05.510 --> 00:56:07.180
And we put those
two things together.

00:56:07.180 --> 00:56:10.460
And one very convenient
way of representing this

00:56:10.460 --> 00:56:12.260
is shown in a paper in 1980.

00:56:12.260 --> 00:56:13.710
Let me walk you through it.

00:56:13.710 --> 00:56:17.860
So this curve right here,
this outermost curve,

00:56:17.860 --> 00:56:22.020
represents the solar
spectrum, energy versus number

00:56:22.020 --> 00:56:23.110
of photons.

00:56:23.110 --> 00:56:28.230
So we have essentially
a photon density.

00:56:28.230 --> 00:56:32.030
This is number of photons per
centimeter squared, per second.

00:56:32.030 --> 00:56:35.350
So photon flux, if you will.

00:56:35.350 --> 00:56:39.530
And over here we have the
energy of those photons.

00:56:39.530 --> 00:56:41.820
And so what this is
meant to represent

00:56:41.820 --> 00:56:43.760
is the cumulative
solar spectrum,

00:56:43.760 --> 00:56:46.037
going from a high
energy here all the way

00:56:46.037 --> 00:56:47.120
down to the lowest energy.

00:56:47.120 --> 00:56:51.380
So we're essentially adding
the different components,

00:56:51.380 --> 00:56:52.940
cumulation plot.

00:56:52.940 --> 00:56:58.500
And if we have a photon energy
in excess of the band gap

00:56:58.500 --> 00:57:01.270
energy, as would be the case,
say, for example three eV

00:57:01.270 --> 00:57:06.830
photon, and let's say the band
gap is 1.35 eV, represented

00:57:06.830 --> 00:57:08.660
by this straight
line right here,

00:57:08.660 --> 00:57:11.146
this energy is going to be lost.

00:57:11.146 --> 00:57:12.770
And so by drawing
this cumulation plot,

00:57:12.770 --> 00:57:17.750
we're plotting the area here,
the energy area that is lost

00:57:17.750 --> 00:57:20.710
to us due to thermalization.

00:57:20.710 --> 00:57:24.390
We could also say that if
the photons have an energy

00:57:24.390 --> 00:57:29.510
less than the band gap, that is
going to be lost to us as well.

00:57:29.510 --> 00:57:32.750
And what we're left with is
a little box that represents

00:57:32.750 --> 00:57:34.810
the total usable
photons, the usable

00:57:34.810 --> 00:57:39.160
photons that we
can extract device.

00:57:39.160 --> 00:57:41.120
This particular
plot is a little bit

00:57:41.120 --> 00:57:43.970
complicated, because
it contains two curves.

00:57:43.970 --> 00:57:45.640
One is this one right here.

00:57:45.640 --> 00:57:47.930
The other one is
this one right here.

00:57:47.930 --> 00:57:53.100
This second curve represents
another realistic loss

00:57:53.100 --> 00:57:55.390
mechanism that we
didn't talk about yet.

00:57:55.390 --> 00:58:00.560
And that is why the extractable
work, represented as w,

00:58:00.560 --> 00:58:02.399
is going to be less
than the band gap energy

00:58:02.399 --> 00:58:03.440
of our solar cell device.

00:58:03.440 --> 00:58:07.650
So if the band gap is 1.35
eV, the total usable work

00:58:07.650 --> 00:58:11.350
would be 0.9 eV, we'll get
to that in a lecture or two.

00:58:11.350 --> 00:58:13.170
And that's why
the white box here

00:58:13.170 --> 00:58:18.950
is going to be smaller than this
horizontal line box over there.

00:58:18.950 --> 00:58:24.240
But it gives you a very first
approximation, a very easy way

00:58:24.240 --> 00:58:28.020
to describe the different losses
that can occur in a solar cell,

00:58:28.020 --> 00:58:31.990
and quickly visualize
them here, thermalization.

00:58:31.990 --> 00:58:34.030
Over here, non-absorption.

00:58:34.030 --> 00:58:38.990
And plot them out very
nicely as the total area

00:58:38.990 --> 00:58:40.580
and representative
area fractions.

00:58:40.580 --> 00:58:42.080
And that's why you
can see here that

00:58:42.080 --> 00:58:46.970
the total usable
solar energy is going

00:58:46.970 --> 00:58:50.110
to be somewhere around 30%.

00:58:50.110 --> 00:58:52.860
This band gap right
here, around 1.35 eV

00:58:52.860 --> 00:58:56.050
is actually pretty near
optimal for the solar spectrum.

00:58:56.050 --> 00:58:59.800
You can imagine if we
increase the band gap energy,

00:58:59.800 --> 00:59:01.930
we would be doing
something like this.

00:59:01.930 --> 00:59:04.400
So we would draw another
box right around here.

00:59:04.400 --> 00:59:07.230
This would be the new
band gap, instead of 1.35,

00:59:07.230 --> 00:59:08.760
that would be out here.

00:59:08.760 --> 00:59:10.260
If we increase the
band gap further,

00:59:10.260 --> 00:59:12.400
we might have something
that looks like that.

00:59:12.400 --> 00:59:13.990
And the area of this
little rectangle

00:59:13.990 --> 00:59:17.441
would be much smaller than
the area of this rectangle.

00:59:17.441 --> 00:59:19.940
Likewise, if we said, OK, we're
going to shrink our band gap

00:59:19.940 --> 00:59:25.062
energy to avoid
non-absorption loss,

00:59:25.062 --> 00:59:27.270
we're going to have an excess
of thermalization loss.

00:59:27.270 --> 00:59:30.280
We'll have a very narrow
rectangle, right, like this,

00:59:30.280 --> 00:59:32.522
and all of this would be loss.

00:59:32.522 --> 00:59:34.480
The solar spectrum,
obviously, does not change.

00:59:34.480 --> 00:59:39.680
This line right here this
is fixed, it's constant.

00:59:39.680 --> 00:59:41.380
You folks kind of see it?

00:59:41.380 --> 00:59:42.470
Beginning to grasp it?

00:59:42.470 --> 00:59:46.860
This is a convenient way of
representing the total usable

00:59:46.860 --> 00:59:50.560
portion of the solar spectrum
from a given semiconductor

00:59:50.560 --> 00:59:52.520
material.

00:59:52.520 --> 00:59:55.261
You can begin seeing the trade
offs between different material

00:59:55.261 --> 00:59:55.760
systems.

00:59:55.760 --> 00:59:57.843
You can say, what happens
if I change my band gap?

00:59:57.843 --> 01:00:00.050
How would that change
the fraction of photons,

01:00:00.050 --> 01:00:02.510
or fraction of photon
energy not absorbed?

01:00:02.510 --> 01:00:05.920
Or fraction of photon energy
lost due to thermalization.

01:00:05.920 --> 01:00:07.640
And you can also
see what happens

01:00:07.640 --> 01:00:09.660
if you-- what would
be an easy way

01:00:09.660 --> 01:00:12.390
to extract more
potential for the sun?

01:00:12.390 --> 01:00:16.440
Instead of just using one
semiconductor material, you?

01:00:16.440 --> 01:00:17.072
More than one.

01:00:17.072 --> 01:00:17.655
More than one.

01:00:17.655 --> 01:00:17.710
Right.

01:00:17.710 --> 01:00:19.876
So now you're drawing
different boxes that represent

01:00:19.876 --> 01:00:20.912
the different materials.

01:00:20.912 --> 01:00:22.370
And if you stack
them right, you're

01:00:22.370 --> 01:00:25.730
able to capture more of
this total area, more

01:00:25.730 --> 01:00:29.310
of the total solar spectrum.

01:00:29.310 --> 01:00:32.220
So this is a really cool plot.

01:00:32.220 --> 01:00:35.927
A lot of good work back
in the 1970s, 1980s.

01:00:35.927 --> 01:00:37.510
If you recall from
lecture number one,

01:00:37.510 --> 01:00:41.500
this was the first wave of
real hardcore solar science,

01:00:41.500 --> 01:00:43.620
after the initial
Bell Labs invention.

01:00:43.620 --> 01:00:47.505
When we had the OPEC oil crises,
and there was a large rush

01:00:47.505 --> 01:00:49.150
of funding into solar research.

01:00:49.150 --> 01:00:51.525
So you had a lot of good work
coming out from those days.

01:00:54.900 --> 01:00:56.730
This next plot that
I'm going to show you

01:00:56.730 --> 01:01:04.650
represents the area of this box
relative to the solar spectrum,

01:01:04.650 --> 01:01:08.270
the percentage of
light that is usable,

01:01:08.270 --> 01:01:10.330
the balance between
non-absorption thermalization

01:01:10.330 --> 01:01:12.146
losses as a function
of band gap energy.

01:01:12.146 --> 01:01:14.020
So if the band gap is
too small, again, we're

01:01:14.020 --> 01:01:15.420
losing a lot of energy
due to thermalization.

01:01:15.420 --> 01:01:17.500
If the band gap's too
large, a lot of energy

01:01:17.500 --> 01:01:19.350
we're losing to non-absorption.

01:01:19.350 --> 01:01:22.010
And somewhere in the
middle is our happy medium.

01:01:22.010 --> 01:01:24.550
These little symbols here
represent different materials.

01:01:24.550 --> 01:01:26.008
Cadmium sulfide,
cadmium telluride,

01:01:26.008 --> 01:01:28.330
gallium arsenide, indium
phosphide, silicon, germanium,

01:01:28.330 --> 01:01:31.870
and so forth, and
calculated efficiencies.

01:01:31.870 --> 01:01:34.140
So I'm going to go into
one advanced concept,

01:01:34.140 --> 01:01:36.300
the multi-junction devices.

01:01:36.300 --> 01:01:39.150
And we just talked
about this box here

01:01:39.150 --> 01:01:43.100
representing the usable energy
from the solar spectrum.

01:01:43.100 --> 01:01:47.160
Now if we go to an absurd
case of 36 band gaps.

01:01:47.160 --> 01:01:51.170
If we imagine 36 materials
with graded band gaps,

01:01:51.170 --> 01:01:53.890
starting from large band
gap at the top to small band

01:01:53.890 --> 01:01:57.030
gap at the back, you
can envision almost

01:01:57.030 --> 01:01:58.950
approximating the entire curve.

01:01:58.950 --> 01:02:02.290
And you can estimate
what the upper efficiency

01:02:02.290 --> 01:02:05.110
limit would be with many band
gaps inside of your material.

01:02:05.110 --> 01:02:08.960
So for one band gap,
somewhere around 37,

01:02:08.960 --> 01:02:10.930
we'll have an entire
lecture dedicated

01:02:10.930 --> 01:02:12.850
to calculating that number.

01:02:12.850 --> 01:02:14.460
For two band gaps
somewhere around 50.

01:02:14.460 --> 01:02:16.330
For three band gaps, 56.

01:02:16.330 --> 01:02:19.450
For 36 band gaps around 72.

01:02:19.450 --> 01:02:22.500
So you can begin seeing how
the efficiency of solar energy

01:02:22.500 --> 01:02:26.210
conversion changes as you
change or add materials,

01:02:26.210 --> 01:02:28.130
you move materials
to your system.

01:02:28.130 --> 01:02:31.300
So how do you practically
do that in a real device?

01:02:31.300 --> 01:02:34.114
Well one method is to put one
material on top of another,

01:02:34.114 --> 01:02:35.780
much like it's
demonstrated right there.

01:02:35.780 --> 01:02:37.850
You have E versus x.

01:02:37.850 --> 01:02:41.320
So I have my E versus x, and
I have multiple materials.

01:02:41.320 --> 01:02:45.610
Another way to do it would be
to use optics to split our light

01:02:45.610 --> 01:02:46.530
into different colors.

01:02:46.530 --> 01:02:50.990
So if we have polychromatic
or multi-colored light coming

01:02:50.990 --> 01:02:53.020
into our system, we
somehow have a set

01:02:53.020 --> 01:02:56.172
of optics put up that
reflect one color, or one

01:02:56.172 --> 01:02:57.880
band of the solar
spectrum, while letting

01:02:57.880 --> 01:03:00.550
the other portion of the
solar spectrum through it.

01:03:00.550 --> 01:03:03.490
And we have different solar
cells with different band gaps,

01:03:03.490 --> 01:03:06.070
each matched to
the incident light.

01:03:06.070 --> 01:03:09.190
Each matched to the
particular color of light.

01:03:09.190 --> 01:03:13.370
Notice this paper, 1982,
this concept was out.

01:03:13.370 --> 01:03:16.320
So again, during that first
wave of real photovoltaics

01:03:16.320 --> 01:03:20.920
innovation in the late
1970s and early 1980s.

01:03:20.920 --> 01:03:23.750
And this was coming right
out of Lincoln Laboratory.

01:03:23.750 --> 01:03:26.990
This is about 35
minutes north of here.

01:03:26.990 --> 01:03:32.280
And this group at the time, the
group number continues to exist

01:03:32.280 --> 01:03:33.854
and is in operation
at Lincoln Labs.

01:03:33.854 --> 01:03:35.770
So most of the people
have moved on obviously,

01:03:35.770 --> 01:03:40.000
but several of the ideas
continue to this day.

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:41.550
There was a more
recent incarnation

01:03:41.550 --> 01:03:45.390
in 2009 of a spectral splitter,
a very similar concept

01:03:45.390 --> 01:03:47.270
as you can see,
optics to concentrate

01:03:47.270 --> 01:03:50.400
the light, a dichroic
mirror, meaning

01:03:50.400 --> 01:03:51.900
it reflects certain
wavelengths, let

01:03:51.900 --> 01:03:53.750
another portion of
the spectrum past,

01:03:53.750 --> 01:03:58.140
and solar cell devices down
below absorbing efficiently

01:03:58.140 --> 01:04:00.700
in that region of the spectrum
and avoiding thermalization

01:04:00.700 --> 01:04:04.030
losses, and avoiding
non-absorption losses.

01:04:04.030 --> 01:04:07.380
This was a $50 million
DARPA project, in fact,

01:04:07.380 --> 01:04:11.070
involving University of Delaware
and several other companies.

01:04:11.070 --> 01:04:13.960
And they published
the results in 2009.

01:04:13.960 --> 01:04:16.520
It was one of their wrap
up papers that described

01:04:16.520 --> 01:04:18.090
the results of the project.

01:04:18.090 --> 01:04:19.900
So concepts.

01:04:19.900 --> 01:04:24.360
To this day, this
spectral splitter it's not

01:04:24.360 --> 01:04:26.094
in commercial production.

01:04:26.094 --> 01:04:28.760
What is in commercial production
are the multi-junction devices,

01:04:28.760 --> 01:04:31.140
where you stack one
on top of another.

01:04:31.140 --> 01:04:34.230
And we'll actually be having the
benefit of using some of them

01:04:34.230 --> 01:04:35.210
in class.

01:04:35.210 --> 01:04:38.490
Boeing spectral lab was kind
enough to donate a set of them

01:04:38.490 --> 01:04:40.030
for our class purposes.

01:04:40.030 --> 01:04:42.440
Yes, question.

01:04:42.440 --> 01:04:44.274
AUDIENCE: This is
also basically what

01:04:44.274 --> 01:04:48.170
plants do by having
multiple different pigment

01:04:48.170 --> 01:04:51.092
molecules in leaves, right?

01:04:51.092 --> 01:04:53.835
That would absorb the
different wavelengths?

01:04:53.835 --> 01:04:56.240
PROFESSOR: Well, it's not
exactly separating light

01:04:56.240 --> 01:04:57.560
by optics in that case.

01:04:57.560 --> 01:04:58.490
So the question was--

01:04:58.490 --> 01:04:59.990
AUDIENCE: No, I
mean multi-junction.

01:04:59.990 --> 01:05:01.720
PROFESSOR: Oh, the
multi-junction idea.

01:05:01.720 --> 01:05:05.190
Yes, if you consider
that there is a reaction

01:05:05.190 --> 01:05:07.180
process occurring in series.

01:05:07.180 --> 01:05:09.560
The important
distinguishing feature

01:05:09.560 --> 01:05:12.360
of the multi-junction device
is that the same current

01:05:12.360 --> 01:05:14.220
is flowing through
the entire device.

01:05:14.220 --> 01:05:17.550
So each sub cell has to be
current matched to the others,

01:05:17.550 --> 01:05:19.140
because the cumulative
current output

01:05:19.140 --> 01:05:21.700
is a harmonic mean of each one.

01:05:21.700 --> 01:05:25.850
So in other words, you're
limited by the worst resistor

01:05:25.850 --> 01:05:27.920
in series, if you will.

01:05:27.920 --> 01:05:30.172
So it's very tricky
to engineer properly

01:05:30.172 --> 01:05:31.380
these multi-junction devices.

01:05:31.380 --> 01:05:33.921
You have to be thinking about
the current output for each sub

01:05:33.921 --> 01:05:35.499
cell and match the currents.

01:05:35.499 --> 01:05:37.540
That means you match the
geometry, the thickness,

01:05:37.540 --> 01:05:40.720
but also the resistivity
of each layer and so forth.

01:05:40.720 --> 01:05:44.120
So similar to a
plant, but not quite.

01:05:44.120 --> 01:05:46.460
There are some special
characteristics

01:05:46.460 --> 01:05:49.250
of the inorganic system.

01:05:49.250 --> 01:05:52.040
So we have a small
demonstration.

01:05:52.040 --> 01:05:54.830
I'd like to welcome Joe
up to the front as well.

01:05:54.830 --> 01:05:57.080
We have a small demonstration
of a few of the concepts

01:05:57.080 --> 01:05:58.870
that we've covered
today in class.

01:05:58.870 --> 01:06:01.710
We're going to be exciting
silicon with light,

01:06:01.710 --> 01:06:04.920
and we're going to be monitoring
the current output using

01:06:04.920 --> 01:06:09.320
this little resistance
measurement device right here.

01:06:09.320 --> 01:06:11.560
So actually I think it's
set to a current readout.

01:06:11.560 --> 01:06:12.434
Yes, current readout.

01:06:12.434 --> 01:06:16.040
So it's in microamps right now,
probably going to milliamps.

01:06:16.040 --> 01:06:16.760
Is that right?

01:06:16.760 --> 01:06:18.470
OK, so milliamp current readout.

01:06:18.470 --> 01:06:20.960
Let me explain to you
what we have right here.

01:06:20.960 --> 01:06:25.530
We have a bare piece of
silicon, and two electric leads

01:06:25.530 --> 01:06:26.370
on either side.

01:06:26.370 --> 01:06:29.160
So a bare piece of
silicon, no device.

01:06:29.160 --> 01:06:31.340
Just a piece of silicon.

01:06:31.340 --> 01:06:33.810
And we have electrical leads
coming out of either side.

01:06:33.810 --> 01:06:36.130
We have a very low resistance
contact on either end.

01:06:36.130 --> 01:06:37.546
For those who are
curious, we used

01:06:37.546 --> 01:06:39.880
a mixture of indium and
gallium, soldering iron,

01:06:39.880 --> 01:06:42.690
scratch the surface, penetrated
the native surface oxide,

01:06:42.690 --> 01:06:44.920
and put the electrical
leads on either side.

01:06:44.920 --> 01:06:48.050
And we have this
connected in series here

01:06:48.050 --> 01:06:51.730
to our current readout device.

01:06:51.730 --> 01:06:56.830
So now what we're going to do is
we're going to illuminate this.

01:06:56.830 --> 01:07:00.370
And again, bare silicon
leads on either side,

01:07:00.370 --> 01:07:02.450
and we're going to be
passing the current

01:07:02.450 --> 01:07:04.680
through the current
measurement system.

01:07:04.680 --> 01:07:06.300
Before we turn it
on, we're going

01:07:06.300 --> 01:07:09.550
to ask people, how
many people expect

01:07:09.550 --> 01:07:12.550
there to be current
driving through the system?

01:07:12.550 --> 01:07:14.600
We have light incident
on the material.

01:07:14.600 --> 01:07:15.700
We're exciting charges.

01:07:15.700 --> 01:07:18.720
Based on today's lecture, there
should be free charges moving

01:07:18.720 --> 01:07:20.080
around that material now.

01:07:20.080 --> 01:07:23.220
How many expect a
current to flow?

01:07:23.220 --> 01:07:24.000
A few.

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:26.130
But a lot of people
shaking their heads.

01:07:26.130 --> 01:07:30.357
Why do you think a
current won't flow?

01:07:30.357 --> 01:07:31.440
There's no electric field.

01:07:31.440 --> 01:07:32.315
There's no potential.

01:07:32.315 --> 01:07:34.460
Why don't we give it a
shot, and why don't we see.

01:07:34.460 --> 01:07:40.770
If we turn this on right
now, what do we see?

01:07:40.770 --> 01:07:41.690
We see zero.

01:07:41.690 --> 01:07:42.200
Right.

01:07:42.200 --> 01:07:44.330
Can some of the folks right
here in the front see?

01:07:44.330 --> 01:07:46.390
Says zero.

01:07:46.390 --> 01:07:49.149
All right, so what this
is telling us again,

01:07:49.149 --> 01:07:51.690
you're welcome to come up after
class and take a closer look.

01:07:51.690 --> 01:07:55.300
What this is telling us here is
that yes, what we talked about

01:07:55.300 --> 01:07:56.519
in class is important today.

01:07:56.519 --> 01:07:58.060
Yes, it's all very
important and it's

01:07:58.060 --> 01:08:01.070
the foundation of calculating
ultimate solar cell

01:08:01.070 --> 01:08:03.410
efficiency, how the material
absorbs the light, how

01:08:03.410 --> 01:08:04.740
charge is excited.

01:08:04.740 --> 01:08:06.590
But we need something else too.

01:08:06.590 --> 01:08:09.220
Once the charge is
excited, somehow we

01:08:09.220 --> 01:08:11.840
have to give it an incentive
to leave the material.

01:08:11.840 --> 01:08:14.229
We have to have a field.

01:08:14.229 --> 01:08:16.520
In this case, we're going to
be using an applied field,

01:08:16.520 --> 01:08:18.920
a couple of batteries.

01:08:18.920 --> 01:08:21.250
So total voltage around
three volts, applied

01:08:21.250 --> 01:08:25.310
across that small material.

01:08:25.310 --> 01:08:27.600
But in a solar
cell device, we're

01:08:27.600 --> 01:08:30.270
going to have a built
in electric field

01:08:30.270 --> 01:08:32.757
that we'll engineer
into the device.

01:08:32.757 --> 01:08:34.590
And we'll talk about
that over next lecture.

01:08:34.590 --> 01:08:37.800
So just for purposes of sanity,
we have our batteries now

01:08:37.800 --> 01:08:40.720
connected in series, and
is now applying a potential

01:08:40.720 --> 01:08:42.000
across those two leads.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:44.477
And now if we turn on the
light, what do we expect?

01:08:44.477 --> 01:08:46.310
We expect to see some
current going through.

01:08:50.750 --> 01:08:55.840
And voila, we have a
current running through it.

01:08:55.840 --> 01:08:58.319
So now, what is the
nature of that current?

01:08:58.319 --> 01:09:00.821
If we move the light closer,
we see the number go up.

01:09:00.821 --> 01:09:02.279
What is the nature
of that current?

01:09:02.279 --> 01:09:04.700
That current is photo excited.

01:09:04.700 --> 01:09:06.700
That current is
exciting electrons

01:09:06.700 --> 01:09:08.979
from the valence band,
from bound states,

01:09:08.979 --> 01:09:11.370
into the conduction band,
it's unbound states,

01:09:11.370 --> 01:09:13.450
where they can move freely
across the material.

01:09:13.450 --> 01:09:15.450
And now, because we have
that potential applied

01:09:15.450 --> 01:09:18.050
across the material, there's
an incentive for them

01:09:18.050 --> 01:09:19.550
to drift in one direction.

01:09:19.550 --> 01:09:23.260
The net flow of electrons
is in one direction.

01:09:23.260 --> 01:09:27.029
We have a drift current in our
material, in our semiconductor,

01:09:27.029 --> 01:09:29.010
and hence we have
the flow of charge

01:09:29.010 --> 01:09:32.060
that is readable by this
current meter right here.

01:09:32.060 --> 01:09:35.729
So without the light,
we have no current.

01:09:35.729 --> 01:09:38.819
With the light, we have current
flowing through the material.

01:09:38.819 --> 01:09:40.740
But current and
light-- actually light

01:09:40.740 --> 01:09:44.189
is not the only thing necessary
to create that output current.

01:09:44.189 --> 01:09:46.396
We also need the potential.

01:09:46.396 --> 01:09:48.479
So next class we'll be
talking about the potential

01:09:48.479 --> 01:09:51.370
and how that's created inside
of a solar cell device.

